Wales Assembly members concerned about ‘passing for puppets’
Welsh MPs are appalled by a proposal to replace their title with the acronym MWP (Member of the Welsh Parliament).
This proposal stems from the proposed amendment of the name of the Assembly, which would become the Welsh Parliament.
In the political sphere, members of the Assembly believe that this could be the subject of taunts.
A Labour MP said his group is concerned that the acronym “rhymes with Twp and Pwp.”
For non-Wales readers: in Welsh, twp means stupid, and pwp means crap.
According to one of its members, the Plaid Cymru (Party of Wales) is not "satisfied" and has proposed other formulas.
The Conservative party would be “open” to a name change, but noted that between MWP and Muppet (puppet), the distance is narrow.
In this context, in Welsh, the letter w is pronounced as the letter u in English of the Yorkshire region.
The Assembly Committee, which is currently preparing the legislation introducing the name change, has indicated that “the final decision regarding the naming of the members of the Assembly belongs to the latter”.
The Government of Wales Act of 2017 gives the Welsh Assembly the power to change its name.
In June, the Commission published the results of a public consultation on the proposal to designate the Assembly as the Welsh Parliament, which was widely supported.
On the question of the title of members, the Commission leans in favour of Members of the Welsh Parliament (or WMP); however, a large majority of Welsh prefer MWP.
It seems that members of the Assembly are making other suggestions, but the effort to reach consensus could prove to be a real headache for Elin Jones, the Speaker of the Assembly, who is expected to submit a name change bill in the coming weeks.
Reform legislation will include other changes to the functioning of the Assembly, including rules on the exclusion of members and the design of the committee system.
The members of the Assembly will take the final decision on the name issue during the debate on the bill.
