“The sea is ours”: Bolivia, blocked, hopes that the court will reopen the way to the Pacific
Sailors patrol an armored boat in the La Paz Naval Headquarters.
Public buildings carry a blue flag like the ocean.
From Lake Titicaca to the Amazon, the naval bases display the following bike: “The sea returns to us by right.
Recovering it is a duty.”
Throughout blocked Bolivia, the memory of a coastline lost to Chile during a bloody resource conflict in the 19th century is still present, as is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean, once again.
These hopes have not been so palpable for several decades, as Bolivia awaits a decision of the International Court of Justice, which will be delivered on 1 October, after five years of deliberations.
“Bolivia has the will, a spirit of unity and serenity, and of course expects a positive result,” said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will follow the decision of the International Court of Justice on the big screen throughout the country, hoping that the court in The Hague will decide in favor of the Bolivian request. Bolivia hopes that, after decades of sporadic negotiations, Chile will be required to negotiate the agreement of a sovereign passage to the ocean to Bolivia.
Evo Morales, Bolivia’s charismatic indigenous president (who faces a controversial fight for re-election next year), also has a lot to say about the decision that will be handed down on Monday.
“We are so close to being able to return to the Pacific Ocean,” he said in late August.
But some analysts believe that the court is unlikely to rule in favour of Chile, and that little would change, even if a positive decision was made.
The Netherlands-based UN body does not have the power to grant Chilean territory, and has stipulated that it will not determine the outcome of any talks.
The fact that the International Court of Justice makes its decision six months after the last arguments shows that the case “was not complicated,” says Paz Zarate, a Chilean expert in international law.
And far from favoring the cause of Bolivia, the last four years have perhaps even harmed it.
“The problem of access to the sea has been hijacked by the current Bolivian administration,” said Zarate.
Morales’ bellicose rhetoric undermined all remaining Chilean goodwill, she suggested.
Bolivia and Chile will continue to exchange, but after that it will be very complicated to hold talks.
The last exchange of ambassadors between the two countries took place in 1962.
Former President Eduardo Rodriguez Veltzé, who represents Bolivia in The Hague, rejected the Court’s decision-making as abnormally fast.
Monday will bring Bolivia “an extraordinary opportunity to start a new era of relations with Chile” and a chance to “end 139 years of disagreements with mutual benefits,” he said.
Calzadilla also challenged the fact that Morales - who remains to this day one of the most popular presidents in Latin America - was using the maritime problem as a political crutch.
“Bolivia will never give up its right of access to the Pacific Ocean,” he added.
“The Court’s decision is an opportunity to see that we have to let go of the past.”
