John Edward: Language skills are essential to the citizens of the world
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence. This trend continued in 2018 with excellent new exam results reinforced by collective and individual success in sports, art, music and other community activities.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS) strive to provide the highest level of service to students and their parents.
Independent schools work to prepare their students for higher education, the career they have chosen, and their place as global citizens.
As an education sector able to design and implement a tailor-made school curriculum, we find that contemporary languages remain popular and desired subjects in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, you speak to his head.
If you speak to him in his language, you speak to his heart.”
It reminds us that we cannot rely on English to build relationships and build trust with people in other countries.
If we look at the excellent exam results this year, we see that languages are at the top of the ranking, with the highest success rates in independent schools.
In total, 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved the highest grade, A.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, shows that 72% of students achieved the highest grade, A, in Mandarin, as did 72% of students who studied German, 69% of students who studied French and 63% of students who studied Spanish.
This shows that Scotland’s independent schools support foreign languages as absolutely essential skills for children and young people in the future.
From now on, languages as subjects are organized just like science, technology, engineering and mathematics in the curricula of independent schools and other schools.
A UK Employment and Skills Commission survey conducted in 2014 found that among the difficulties employers face in recruiting candidates, 17% are related to insufficient language skills.
Language skills are therefore increasingly vital in preparing young people for their future careers.
With more job opportunities requiring languages, these skills are essential in our globalized world.
Regardless of career choice, a person who speaks a second language will have a real advantage in the future thanks to this long-lasting skill.
Being able to communicate directly with strangers will automatically put the multilingual person ahead of their competitors.
According to a 2013 YouGov survey of 4,000 adults living in the United Kingdom, 75% of them did not have sufficient command of a foreign language to hold a conversation. French was the only language spoken by a double-digit percentage (15%).
This is why investing in language learning is important for children today.
By speaking multiple languages, especially those in emerging economies, children will have a better chance of finding a rewarding job.
In Scotland, each school will teach different languages.
Many will focus on contemporary classical languages, while others will teach languages considered important to the UK in the run-up to 2020, including Mandarin and Japanese.
Whatever your child’s preferences, several languages will be available in independent schools, with specialist staff in the field.
Scottish independent schools want to offer a learning environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
It is clear that, in today's global business environment, languages remain of paramount importance for the future of the country, and this must be reflected in education.
Modern languages should be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to Scottish youth.
We have to do it.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
