North Korea says disarmament can never be done unilaterally without confidence.
On Saturday, the North Korean foreign minister told the United Nations that maintaining the sanctions reinforced his mistrust of the United States and that it would be impossible for his country to unilaterally renounce its nuclear weapons in these circumstances.
At the world body's annual general meeting, Ri Yong Ho said North Korea had taken "important steps of good will" last year, such as ending nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and its commitment not to proliferate nuclear weapons and technology.
"However, we see no corresponding response from the United States," he said.
In the absence of confidence in the United States, we will fear for our national security and, in such circumstances, we cannot be the first to disarm unilaterally.”
While reiterating North Korea’s well-known criticism of Washington’s opposition to a “step-by-step” approach to denuclearization under which North Korea would be rewarded if it gradually took action, its statement proved important in that it did not reject the idea of unilateral denuclearization as Pyongyang had done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump on June 12 in Singapore at the first-ever summit between a sitting U.S. president and a North Korean leader, when Kim pledged to work towards a “denuclearization of the Korean peninsula” while Trump promised to guarantee North Korea’s security.
North Korea is seeking to officially end the Korean War (1950-1953), but the United States has said Pyongyang must first give up its nuclear weapons.
Washington has also refused demands to ease tough international sanctions against North Korea.
The U.S. insists that North Korea first proceed with denuclearization and step up pressure by imposing sanctions to achieve their goal in a coercive manner, even opposing the “end-of-war declaration.”
“Those who think that these sanctions can make us pander do not know us.
The problem is that maintaining sanctions increases our mistrust.”
Ri did not comment on the second summit between Kim and Trump that the US leader highlighted at the United Nations earlier this week.
Instead, the minister pointed to three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months, and added: “If the part concerned with the denuclearization issue was South Korea and not the United States, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be in such a deadlock.”
Still, the tone of Ri’s speech was radically different from last year’s, when he told the UN General Assembly that it was inevitable to point North Korean missiles at North American territory after the “evil” President Trump called Kim a “missile man” on a suicide mission.
Trump, who threatened last year at the United Nations to “totally destroy” North Korea, has been praised this year for the courage with which Kim has applied measures towards disarmament, but added that there is still much to be done and that sanctions will not be lifted until North Korea disarms.
On Wednesday, Trump said no deadline had been set: “It can take two years, three years or five months; it doesn’t matter,” he said.
China and Russia argue that the UN Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the measures adopted.
However, US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the UN Security Council last Thursday that “the implementation of Security Council sanctions must be firmly and systematically maintained until denuclearization is complete, final and verified.”
The Security Council has unanimously tightened sanctions against North Korea since 2006 in order to stifle funding for Pyongyang’s nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then announced that he would return to Pyongyang next month to prepare for a second summit.
This year Pompeo has already visited North Korea three times, but his last trip was somewhat disastrous.
In July, he left Pyongyang claiming that progress had been made, but in the hours that followed, North Korea denounced its “gangster methods.”
In a meeting with Moon this month, North Korea pledged to dismantle a missile site as well as a nuclear complex if the U.S. took “equivalent steps.”
According to the South Korean president, Kim is demanding the security guarantees promised by Trump in Singapore, and efforts to normalize relations with Washington.
Harvard: Students Take Rest Classes
This year, Harvard University introduced a new course that allows all undergraduate students to sleep more and combats the growing macho trend of studying by consuming caffeine all night long.
A professor has noticed that most students at the best university in the world do not know how to take care of them
This course, designed by Charles Czeisler, professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, is the first of its kind in the United States.
It was after giving a lecture on the effects of sleep deprivation on learning that the idea came to him.
In the end, a student approached me and said, “Why am I told this only in the last year?”
She said no one ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me,” he told The Telegraph.
Delivered for the first time this year, this course explains to students the need to adopt good sleep habits to improve their academic and physical performance, as well as their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and general manager of the university's health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after finding that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The class time consists of different interactive exercises.
One of the sections presents the image of a dormitory containing different objects (coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, books...) on which students click to know the effects of caffeine and light, as well as the impact of lack of sleep on their physical performance and the importance of integrating a routine before bedtime.
In another section, participants learn how long-term lack of sleep can increase the risk of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
A map of the campus with interactive icons then invites participants to reflect on their daily routine.
“We know it won’t instantly change student behavior.
However, in our opinion, they have the right to know this information – in the same way that you have the right to know what the health effects of smoking are,” added Professor Czeisler.
According to him, the pride culture of “getting a sleepless night” still exists, and he adds that modern technology and the ever-increasing pressure on students make lack of sleep a growing problem.
Having enough and good quality sleep should be students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he said – even to avoid gaining weight, as lack of sleep puts the brain into starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old California chemistry and physical biology student, helped Professor Czeisler design this course after being one of his students last year, during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and pushed him to insist that it be offered to the entire campus.
He hopes that the next step will be to offer all postgraduate students a similar degree program before joining the reputable institution.
Professor Czeisler recommends that students set an alarm for both bedtime and wake time, and be aware of the harmful effects of “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED light, which can disrupt their circadian rhythm and lead to sleep disorders.
