Almanac: The inventor of the Geiger counter
And now, a page from our Almanac "Sunday Morning": On September 30, 1882, 136 years ago today, and THE TOURNE ACCOUNTEUR... was born the future physicist Johannes Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger, in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity; an invention that later gave rise to the device known as the Geiger counter.
A pillar of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become fundamental in pop culture, as can be seen in the 1950 film “Bells of Coronado,” starring Roy Rogers and Dale Evans, two unlikely scientists:
A man: “What is this?”
Rogers: "It's a Geiger meter, it's used to look for radioactive minerals, like uranium.
Thanks to these headphones, one can really hear the effects of atoms released into the minerals by radioactivity.”
Evans: “Say, it’s sure to jump right now!”
“Hans” Geiger died in 1945, a few days before his 63rd birthday.
But the invention that bears his name remains.
New cancer vaccine allows immune system to ‘detect’ cancer cells
New cancer vaccine allows immune system to ‘detect’ cancer cells and kill them
As part of the treatment, the vaccine tells the immune system how to recognize cancer cells
This technique involves extracting immune cells from a patient and modifying them in the laboratory.
