What is the Global Citizen Festival and has it done anything to reduce poverty?
This Saturday, New York City will host the Global Citizen Festival, an annual music event with a very impressive list of stars and an equally impressive mission: to end global poverty.
The Global Citizen Festival, now in its seventh edition, will see tens of thousands of people flock to Central Park’s Great Lawn to not only enjoy performances by artists such as Janet Jackson, Cardi B and Shawn Mendes, but also raise awareness of the festival’s true goal of ending extreme poverty by 2030.
The Global Citizen Festival, which first took place in 2012, is an extension of the Global Poverty Project, an international advocacy group that hopes to eradicate poverty by increasing the number of people actively fighting it.
In order to receive a free ticket to the event (unless you’re willing to pay for a VIP ticket), spectators had to complete a series of tasks, or “actions,” such as volunteering, emailing a global leader, calling, or making any other useful effort to raise awareness of the fight against poverty.
But to what extent can the Global Citizen organization still achieve its goal in the remaining 12 years?
Does the idea of rewarding people with a free concert really persuade them to demand a call to action, or is it just another example of “clictivism” – a situation in which people really think they can make a difference by signing a petition or tweeting?
Since 2011, Global Citizen has recorded more than 19 million “actions” from its supporters, who advocate for many different goals.
According to the organization, these actions have helped inspire world leaders to make commitments and adopt policies amounting to more than $37 billion that are expected to change the lives of more than 2.25 billion people by 2030.
At the beginning of 2018, the group mentioned 390 commitments and announcements resulting from its actions, of which a tranche of at least $10 billion has already been disbursed or raised.
The group estimates that guaranteed funds have so far had a direct impact on nearly 649 million people around the world.
Key commitments include The Power of Nutrition, a UK-based partnership of investors and implementers who are committed to “helping children reach their full potential,” while promising Rwanda a 35 million pound aid package to end malnutrition in the country after receiving more than 4,700 messages from Global Citizens.
“Thanks to the support of the UK government, donors, national governments and Global Citizens like you, we can make the social injustice of undernutrition a footnote in history,” Tracey Ullman, ambassador for The Power of Nutrition program, told the crowd at a concert in London in April 2018.
The group also said that following the company’s more than 5,000 actions to ask the UK to improve maternal and child nutrition, the government has announced funding for a project, The Power of Nutrition, which will benefit 5 million women and children through nutrition interventions.
In response to one of the most frequently asked questions on its website, “What makes you think it’s possible to end extreme poverty?”
Global Citizen said: “The road to getting there will be long and difficult, sometimes we will fall and fail.
However, like the major civil rights and anti-apartheid movements before us, we will succeed because we are more powerful together.
Janet Jackson, The Weeknd, Shawn Mendes, Cardi B, Janelle Monèe are among the artists who will perform this year in New York, where Debora-Lee Furness and Hugh Jackman will host the show.
