World Wide Web Inventor Considers Launching New Internet to Challenge Google and Facebook
Tim Berners-Lee, the inventor of the World Wide Web, is launching a brand new company that seeks to compete with Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technological legend, Inrupt, is a company that takes advantage of Berners-Lee’s free platform Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where their data is saved as well as who is allowed to access such and such information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee joked that Inrupt was aiming to “dominate the world.”
“We have to do it now,” he said of the launch.
“This is a historic moment.”
The app uses Solid’s technology to allow people to create their own “online personal data store” or DPL.
It can contain contact lists, to-do lists, a calendar, a music library and other personal and professional tools.
It’s like Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack, and Spotify are all available at the same time on a single browser.
The peculiarity of the online personal data store is that it is entirely up to the user to decide who can access what type of information.
The company calls this “personal responsibility via data.”
According to the company’s CEO, John Bruce, the idea behind Inrupt is that the company brings the right resources, processes and skills to make Solid accessible to everyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, a few developers working on contract on the project and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world will be able to build their own decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not yet in discussions with “Facebook and Google” about whether or not to make a complete change where all their business models are completely messed up in an instant.
“We’re not asking them for permission.”
In an article on Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that “[Inrupt’s] mission is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem to protect the integrity and quality of the new web built on Solid.”
In 1994, at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet by creating the World Wide Web Consortium.
Over the past few months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the debate over net neutrality.
Although he launched Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Web Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about this new era of the web,” Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann: Celebration of a First World War clergyman decorated with the Victoria Cross
The only Church of England clergyman to receive the Victoria Cross during World War I as a combatant was celebrated in his hometown 100 years later.
Lieutenant-Colonel Bernard Vann won this distinction on September 29, 1918, during the attack at Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
He was, however, killed by a sniper four days later and was unaware that he had obtained the highest British military distinction.
His two grandsons unveiled a commemorative stone at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
Michael Vann, one of his grandsons, said it was “brilliantly symbolic” to unveil the stone exactly 100 years after his grandfather’s exploit.
According to the London Gazatte, on September 29, 1918, Lieutenant-Colonel Vann led his battalion on the Saint-Quentin Canal “through a very thick fog and under the violent fire of field guns and machine guns.”
Later, he rushed to the firing line and, with "greatest bravery," guided the line before blowing up a field cannon on his own and knocking out three soldiers from the detachment.
On 4 October 1918, a German sniper killed Lieutenant-Colonel Vann, just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “a thing I’ll never be at, but one that humbles me.”
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, also laid a wreath after the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band-led parade.
Michael Vann said he felt "very honored to be part of the parade" and added that "the courage of an authentic hero is reflected in the support that will be given to him by many people."
Mixed martial arts fans stayed up all night watching Bellator 206. Instead, they got Peppa Pig
Imagine that, you spent the whole night watching a well-stocked Bellator 206, but you couldn’t see the main event.
In San Jose, the event had 13 fights, six of them on the main page, and was broadcast live throughout the night in the UK, on Channel 5.
At 6 a.m., as Gegard Mousasi and Rory MacDonald were preparing to face each other, viewers in the UK were stunned when the broadcast changed to Peppa Pig.
Some were unhappy that they stayed awake until the early hours of the morning especially for the fight.
A fan on Twitter described the move to children’s cartoons as “a kind of bad joke.”
Regarding the transmission, Bellator’s senior vice president of marketing and communications, Dave Schwartz, said that “the government regulation states that at 6 a.m., this content was not suitable, so they had to switch to children’s shows.”
“Peppa the pig,” yes.
Scott Coker, the president of Bellator, said they would work on their programming to include British viewers in the future.
“I think when I think about the replay, I think we can probably find a solution,” Coker said.
“However, it is six o’clock in the morning on a Sunday and we will not be able to find a solution until Sunday our time, which is Monday their time.
But we're working on it.
Believe me, when the program switched, there were a lot of messages in both directions and they weren’t all friendly.
We were trying to fix it, we thought it was a technical problem.
But it wasn’t a problem, it was a government issue.
I can guarantee it won't happen next time.
We’ll limit ourselves to five fights instead of six – as we usually do – and we’ve tried to give more for the fans and we’ve ruined everything.
This is a regrettable situation.”
Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt “inferior” in terms of sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley claims to have grown up feeling inferior to others because of his sexuality – but that instilled in him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn’t realize until he went to high school that “not everyone [was] like me.”
On the first show of Radio 4 Desert Island Discs presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he spoke about the issue of gay rights to give others "hope".
He also said that becoming a parent had made him less interested in winning the Olympics.
The show's usual presenter, Kirsty Young, took several months off because of her illness.
Appearing as a castaway on Laverne's first show, Daley said he felt "less than" every other child growing up because "it wasn't socially acceptable to love boys and girls."
He said, “Even today, those feelings of being inferior and different are the real things that have given me the power and strength to succeed.”
In order not to disappoint everyone when they finally learned the truth about his sexuality, he wanted to prove that he was “something,” he continued.
The two-time Olympic bronze medallist is now a prominent LGBT activist and has taken advantage of his participation this year at the Commonwealth Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he was speaking out because he felt lucky to be able to live openly without ramifications and so he wanted to give back “hope” to others.
The three-time world champion claimed he "didn't expect" to fall in love with a man - American filmmaker Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013
Daley last year married the Oscar winner, 20 years his senior, but he said age difference had never been a problem.
"When you see so many things at such a young age" - he took part in his first Olympics at the age of 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was difficult to find a person of the same age having experienced the same ups and downs.
In June, they became parents to a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley claimed that "his whole outlook" had changed.
“If you asked me last year, I was just thinking about winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know what, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
My Olympic gold medal is Robbie.”
His son has the same name as his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 from brain cancer.
Daley said his father did not accept that he was going to die and that one of the last things he asked him was if they already had their tickets for London 2012, since he wanted to be sitting in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘Dad, you’re not going to be in the front row anymore,’” he said.
“I was holding him by the hand when he stopped breathing and he had to stop breathing and he died before I finally recognized that he was not invincible,” he added.
The following year, Daley competed in the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
“That was all I’d dreamed of all my life – diving in front of a home crowd at the Olympics, there’s nothing better,” he said.
In addition, it inspired his first choice of song - Proud by Heather Small - which had accompanied him during the preparations for the Olympics and always gave him goosebumps.
Desert Island Discs is on BBC Radio 4 Sunday at 11:15 a.m., BST.
An out-of-shape Mickelson on the Ryder Cup bench on Saturday
American Phil Mickelson will set a record Sunday playing his 47th game of the Ryder Cup, but he will have to recover to avoid it being an unfortunate stage.
Mickelson, who was competing in the biannual competition for the twelfth time, a record, was ruled out by captain Jim Furyk of Saturday’s fourballs and foursomes.
Instead of being at the heart of the action, as he has so often been for the United States, the five-time great champion has divided his day between the role of supporter and the refinement of his game at the stand in order to remedy his ailments.
He has never been the greatest of the leaders, even at the peak of his career. At 48, he is not the most suitable for the difficult National Golf, where the long rough systematically punishes misguided shots.
And as if the course wasn’t formidable enough in itself, Mickelson, in Sunday’s ninth game, faced British Open winner Francesco Molinari, who teamed up this week with Tommy Fleetwood to win their four games.
If the Americans, four down at the start of the 12 singles games, make a good start, Mickelson’s game could prove to be absolutely crucial.
Furyk expressed his confidence in his man, but he couldn't say much else.
“He fully understood the role he had to play today, gave me a pat on the back, put his arm around me and said he would be ready tomorrow,” Furyk said.
“He has a lot of confidence in him.
He’s a legendary champion and he’s added so much to these teams in the past, just like this week.
I probably didn’t see him play two games.
I was planning more, but that's how it happened and that's how we felt we had to go.
He wants to be there, like everyone else.”
On Sunday, Mickelson will break Nick Faldo’s record for the most Ryder Cup games played.
This could mark the end of a Ryder Cup career that has never quite reached the heights of its individual record.
Mickelson has 18 wins, 20 losses and seven halves to his credit, although Furyk said his presence has brought concrete elements to the team.
He’s funny, sarcastic, witty, he likes to make fun of people, and he’s a great guy to have in the team room,” he explained.
“I think the younger players had fun competing against him this week, which was fun to see.
He does more than just play.”
European team captain Thomas Bjorn knows the lead could soon disappear
Thomas Bjorn, the European captain, knows from experience that a significant lead before the singles of the last day of the Ryder Cup can easily turn into a painful course.
The Dane played his first game in 1997 in Valderrama, where a team captained by Seve Ballesteros was five points ahead of the Americans, but eventually rose to the top of the standings with the smallest possible gap on the finish line, winning 141-2-131-2.
“You keep remembering that we were leading a lot in Valderrama; we had a big lead in Brookline, where we failed, as well as in Valderrama, where we won, but narrowly,” said Bjorn, after watching the 2018 Ranking win 5-3 both Friday and yesterday at the National Golf to lead 10-6.
History will prove to me and to all members of this team that this is not the end.
Go ahead tomorrow.
Go ahead and do whatever it takes.
It's not over until you get the points on the board.
We have a goal, which is to try and win this trophy, and that’s where we have to stay focused.
I’ve always said I’m focused on the 12 players on our side, but we’re very aware of what’s happening on the other side – they’re the best players in the world.”
Delighted with the performance of his players on a challenging golf course, Bjorn added: “I would never step forward on this.
Tomorrow is a completely different pair of sleeves.
Tomorrow, it is the individual performances that will be presented and it is quite different.
It’s fantastic to be with a teammate when things are going well, but when you’re out there on your own, you’re put to the test to the fullest of your ability as a golfer.
That’s the message to the players, is to get the best out of yourself tomorrow.
When you leave your partner behind, he has to get the best out of himself, too.”
Unlike Bjorn, his counterpart Jim Furyk will seek to ensure that his players get better results individually than as teammates, with the exception of Jordan Spieth and Justin Thomas, who got three out of four points.
Furyk himself experienced both ends of these last day’s turnarounds, having been part of the winning team at Brookline before losing at the end of the “Miracle of Medinah”, where Europe snatched the win.
“I remember every word,” he says in response to the question of how Ben Crenshaw, the captain in 1999, had made it to rally his players on the last day.
“We have 12 important games tomorrow, but you’d like to take that quick start like you saw in Brookline, like you saw in Medinah.
This dynamic, when it goes in a direction, puts a lot of pressure on the middle games.
We set up our training accordingly and put the guys as we thought we had to, we’re trying to do magic tomorrow.”
Thomas was assigned the task of leading the counterattack and will face Rory McIlroy in the first-class duel, with Paul Casey, Justin Rose, Jon Rahm, Tommy Fleetwood and Ian Poulter, the other Europeans in the top half of the standings.
“I’ve accompanied this group of guys in that order because I think it covers the whole course,” Bjorn said of his singles selections.
Germany's new warship postponed again
According to local media, the new German Navy frigate should have been commissioned in 2014 to replace the aging warships dating from the Cold War, but it will not be in service until at least next year due to faulty systems and exponential expenses.
According to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quotes a military spokesman, the commissioning of the “Rheinland-Pfalz”, the flagship of the all-new frigates of Baden-Wuerttemberg, has been postponed to the first half of 2019.
The ship should have joined the Navy in 2014, but worrying post-delivery issues have jeopardized the fate of this ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wurttemberg-class ships that the Navy ordered in 2007 will replace the aging Bremen-class frigates.
It is certain that they will be equipped with a powerful gun, a range of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles as well as some stealth technologies, such as a radar, infrared and reduced acoustic signature.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – it should be possible to deploy the latest frigates for up to two years outside the home ports.
According to Die Zeit, however, the incessant delays mean that forward-thinking warships – which should allow Germany to project its force overseas – will already be obsolete when put into service.
Last year, the cursed F125 frigate made headlines when the German Navy officially refused to put the ship into service and sent it back to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
It was the first time the Navy had returned a ship to a shipbuilder after it was delivered.
The reasons for this return were little known, but the German media mentioned a number of “software and hardware flaws” that rendered the warship useless in case of deployment on a combat mission.
The software failures were particularly significant as the Baden-Wurttemberg-class ships will be operated by a crew of about 120 sailors, which corresponds to half of the crews of the old Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it appears that the vessel is significantly overloaded, which decreases its performance and reduces the Navy's ability to make future improvements.
It is estimated that the 7,000-tonne Rheinland-Pfalz weighs twice as much as similar-class ships used by the Germans during World War II.
Beyond computer system failures, the price of the project as a whole – including crew training – is also becoming a problem.
It is said to have reached the astronomical sum of 3.1 billion euros ($3.6 billion), against 2.2 billion initially.
The problems associated with the new frigates are of particular importance in the light of recent warnings that Germany's naval force is diminishing.
Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German parliament’s defense committee, acknowledged earlier this year that the Navy is in fact “short of ships that can deploy.”
The official said the situation had produced a snowball effect over time, as the old ships were decommissioned but no replacement ships were designated.
He regretted that none of the frigates of the Baden-Wuerttemberg class could join the Navy.
The National Trust Monitors the Secret Life of Bats
New research in an area of the Scottish Highlands seeks to reveal how bats use the landscape in their quest for food.
It is hoped that the observations will shed new light on the behaviour of these unique flying mammals and guide future conservation activities.
The National Trust for Scotland researchers’ study will follow common and soprano pipistrelles as well as long-eared brown bats and Daubenton at Inverewe Garden, Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed at key locations around the property to track bat activities throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile studies using hand-held detectors.
A professional sound analysis will determine the frequency of bat cries and the activities of the different species.
A habitat map and report will be prepared to provide a detailed picture of their behaviour across the territory.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the results will reveal the most important habitat areas for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work such as the creation of grasslands and how best to preserve forests for bats and other related species.
In Scotland and the United Kingdom, bat populations have declined significantly over the past century.
They are threatened by construction and development work that affects the perches and leads to the loss of their habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as can fly-papers and certain chemical treatments of building materials, as well as attacks from pet cats.
Bats are not really blind.
However, given their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to capturing prey.
They use a sophisticated echolocation technique to spot insects and obstacles on their flight route.
Responsible for the protection of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, the NTS takes bats very seriously.
It has ten trained experts, who regularly conduct surveys, perch inspections and sometimes rescues.
The organization also established Scotland's first and only bat reserve at the Threave site in Dumfries and Galloway, home to eight of Scotland's ten bat species.
Domain manager David Thompson says the site is the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a great place for bats,” he says.
“We have old buildings, lots of old trees and all the right habitat.
But there’s still a lot to learn about bats, so the work we’re doing here and in other places will help us better understand what bats need to thrive.”
He stresses the importance of checking for bats before maintaining the properties, because by unintentionally destroying a single maternity nest, it can cause the death of 400 females and small, or even the disappearance of an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill, disturb, or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, the Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
She said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and when it comes to many of our species, we don’t know what’s going on in their populations right now.”
Ronaldo denies rape charges as his lawyers prepare to sue German magazine
Cristiano Ronaldo called the rape charges against him “false information,” and claimed that people “want to make themselves known” by using his name.
His lawyers are preparing to sue the German magazine Der Spiegel, which has published the allegations.
The Portugal and Juventus striker was accused of raping an American woman named Kathryn Mayorga in a Las Vegas hotel room in 2009.
He then reportedly paid her $375,000 to keep her quiet about the incident, Der Spiegel said last Friday.
Speaking to his 142 million fans in a video posted live on Instagram hours after the allegations were made, Ronaldo, 33, called the information “false information.”
“No, no, no, no, and no.
What they said today is false information,” the five-time Ballon d’Or winner told the camera.
“They want to advertise using my name.
That's normal.
They want to be famous by saying my name, but it's part of the job.
I’m a happy man and everything is fine,” the player added with a smile.
According to Reuters, Ronaldo’s lawyers are preparing to sue Der Spiegel over the allegations, which they described as “unacceptable accusations of suspicion in the field of privacy.”
Attorney Christian Schertz said the player would seek compensation for “moral damages in an amount commensurate with the seriousness of the offence, which is probably one of the most serious human rights violations in recent years.”
The alleged incident took place in June 2009 in a suite of the hotel-casino Le Palms, in Las Vegas.
After meeting at a nightclub, Ronaldo and Mayorga apparently returned to the player's room, where anal rape allegedly occurred, according to documents filed with Clark County Court in Nevada.
Mayorga says Ronaldo got down on his knees after the alleged incident and assured him that he was a “good guy” at “99%” but that he didn’t know what was going on with the remaining “1%”.
The documents claim that Ronaldo confirmed that the couple had had sex, but that these were consensual.
Mayorga also said she went to police and that photos of her injuries were taken in a hospital, but that she later agreed to an amicable settlement because she felt “terrified of reprisals” and feared “public humiliation.”
The 34-year-old says she is now seeking to cancel the settlement because she remains traumatized by the alleged incident.
Ronaldo was about to join Real Madrid by leaving Manchester United at the time of this alleged assault, and this summer he joined the Italian giant Juve under a contract of 100 million euros.
Brexit: The UK would “forever regret” the departure of car manufacturers.
According to Greg Clark, the UK's trade secretary, "would regret it forever" if it lost its status as a global leader in car manufacturing after Brexit.
He added that it was “worrying” that Toyota UK told the BBC that it would temporarily halt production at its plant in Burnaston, near Derby, if Britain withdrew from the EU without a deal.
“We need a deal,” Clark said.
The Japanese automaker said the impact of border delays in the event of a no-deal Brexit could cost jobs.
The Burnaston plant – which makes Toyota’s Auris and Avensis vehicles – built nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other European Union countries.
“I believe that if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, production will stop at our factory,” said Marvin Cooke, Toyota’s director at Burnaston.
Other British automakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have expressed fears of leaving the EU without an agreement on how cross-border trade will work.
For example, BMW says it will close its Mini plant in Oxford for a month following Brexit.
The biggest concerns are what automakers are calling supply chain risks in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line is operated in “tense flow,” with parts arriving every 37 minutes from UK and EU suppliers for custom-built vehicles.
If on March 29, the UK leaves the EU without a deal, there could be disruptions at the border that the industry says could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to hold inventory for more than a day at its Derbyshire plant, the company said, and so production would be halted.
According to Clark, Theresa May’s Chequers plan for future relations with the EU is “precisely calibrated to avoid these border controls.”
“We want to have the best deal that will allow, as I said, not only to take advantage of the current success, but also to seize this opportunity,” he told the BBC’s Radio 4’s Today.
“The evidence, not only from Toyota but from other manufacturers, is that we absolutely need to be able to maintain what has proven to be an excellent set of supply chains.”
While Toyota has not been able to specify how long production will be halted, it warned that in the longer term, the additional costs would reduce the plant’s competitiveness and end up costing jobs.
Peter Tsouvallaris, the union’s factory coordinator who has worked in Burnaston for 24 years, said its members are increasingly worried: “In my experience, once these jobs go away, they never come back.”
A government spokesman said: “We have proposed a precise and credible plan for our future relationship with the EU.”
White House says Trump and Rosenstein meeting could still be delayed
According to the White House announcement on Sunday, the meeting between Donald Trump and Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be “repeated by a week,” while the fight for Supreme Court candidate Brett Kavanaugh continues.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Robert Mueller, the special adviser charged with investigating Russian interference in the elections, ties between Trump’s aides and Russia, and possible obstructions to justice by the president.
The question of whether or not Trump will fire the assistant attorney general, and thus endanger Mueller’s independence, has been fueling rumors in Washington for months.
Earlier this month, the New York Times reported that Rosenstein had spoken about wearing a microphone in order to record conversations with Trump and the possibility of eliminating the president by the 25th Amendment.
Rosenstein denied these claims.
However, last Monday, he ran for the White House, as he was about to step down.
Instead, a meeting with Trump, who was then at the United Nations in New York, was announced for Thursday.
Trump said he “would rather not” dismiss Rosenstein, but the meeting was postponed to avoid a clash with the Senate Judiciary Committee hearing before which Kavanaugh and Dr. Christine Blasey Ford, one of the women who accused him of sexual assault, testified.
On Friday, Trump asked the FBI to conduct a week-long investigation into the complaints against Kavanaugh, further delaying the Senate vote.
On Sunday, Trump’s press secretary, Sarah Sanders, made an appearance on Fox News.
Asked about the meeting with Rosenstein, she said: "No date has been set for this, it could be this week, I could see if we postpone another week given all the other things that are happening at the Supreme Court.
But we’ll see and I like to keep the press informed.”
The claim would be disputed by some journalists: Since September 10, Sanders has not held any press conferences at the White House.
Chris Wallace asked why.
Sanders replied that the rarity of the lectures was not due to an aversion to “demagogic” TV reporters, although she said, “I have nothing against them amazing the gallery.”
Then she hinted that direct contact between Trump and the press will increase.
Without citing any evidence, she added that “the president participates in more question-and-answer sessions than any other president before him”: “We checked the numbers.”
Press conferences will always take place, Sanders said, but “if the press has the chance to directly question the President of the United States, it’s infinitely better than talking to me.
We try to do it frequently, you’ve seen it well in recent weeks, and it’s going to take the place of a press conference where you can talk to the President of the United States.”
On a regular basis, Trump answers questions when he leaves the White House or when he attends public meetings or press conferences with dignitaries.
It is rare that he does press conferences solo.
This week in New York, the president may have demonstrated why, by making a casual appearance and at times a bizarre appearance in front of the assembled journalists.
On Brexit fears, Health Secretary writes to EU workers at NHS Scotland
The Health Secretary wrote to EU officials working in the Scottish NHS to express the country’s gratitude and wish them to remain in office after Brexit.
Scottish MP Jeane Freeman sent a letter within less than six months before the UK withdrew from the EU.
The Scottish government has already committed to cover the cost of status applications for European citizens working in its decentralised public services.
Freeman wrote in his letter: “During the summer, withdrawal negotiations continued between the UK and the EU and are expected to result in decisions this fall.
But the British government has also stepped up its preparations in the event of a no deal.
I understand that this period must be very troubling for all of you.
That is why I wanted to reiterate how much I value the contribution of each member of staff, regardless of their nationality.
Colleagues from across the EU and beyond bring valuable experience and skills that strengthen and improve the work of health services, and benefit the patients and communities we serve.
Scotland is quite your home and we really want you to stay here.”
After suffering a head injury, Christion Abercrombie undergoes emergency surgery
According to Mike Organ of Tennessee State, Texas Tigers linebacker Christion Abercrombie underwent emergency surgery after a head injury Saturday in the Vanderbilt Commodores 31-27 loss.
Rod Reed, the head coach of the state of Tennessee, told reporters that the injury occurred just before halftime.
“He got to the sidelines and collapsed there,” Reed said.
Coaches and medical staff administered oxygen to Abercrombie on the sideline before placing him on a stretcher and taking him for another exam.
A representative from the state of Tennessee told Chris Harris of WSMV in Nashville, Tennessee, that Abercrombie had come out of the operating room of the Vanderbilt Medical Center.
Harris said there were "no details yet as to the type or extent of the injury" and that the state of Tennessee was trying to determine when the injury occurred.
Abercrombie, a student athlete in his second year, is in his first season with the state of Tennessee after his transfer from Illinois.
He had five total tackles on Saturday before coming out of the game, bringing his season total to 18 tackles.
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty if they buy a property in the UK
Foreign buyers will have to pay higher stamp duties if they buy a property in the UK and the extra money will be used to help the homeless under the new conservative schemes
This measure will undo the success of Corbyn’s campaign to attract young voters
Stamp duty increase will be imposed on those who do not pay tax in the UK
The Treasury expects to raise up to 120 million pounds a year to help the homeless.
Foreign buyers will be subject to a higher stamp duty rate if they buy a property in the UK – the extra money will be used to help the homeless, Theresa May will announce today.
The move will be seen as an initiative to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s campaign to attract younger voters by committing to providing more affordable housing and targeting high-income earners.
The stamp duty increase will be imposed on individuals and businesses that do not pay taxes in the UK, and the extra money will be used to bolster the government’s efforts in the fight to help the homeless.
This surcharge - in addition to the current stamp duty, including the higher levels introduced two years ago on second homes and lease purchases - could be as high as 3%.
The Treasury expects the project to raise up to 120 million pounds a year.
About 13% of London’s new buildings are bought by non-UK residents, which drives up prices and prevents first-time buyers from finding a place in the housing market.
Many of the country’s rich areas – especially in the capital – have become “ghost cities” because of the high number of foreign buyers who mostly stay outside the country.
This new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson demanded a reduction in stamp duty to help more young people acquire a first home.
Accusing large construction companies of keeping property prices high by grabbing land without using it, he urged May to drop quotas on affordable housing in an effort to settle the "real estate disgrace" in the UK.
Corbyn presented an attractive package of housing reform proposals, including rent controls and the removal of “no-fault” evictions.
He also wants to give the councils more powers to build new homes.
May said: “Last year I said that I would dedicate my position as prime minister to the renaissance of the British dream – that every new generation will have a better life.
To do this, we need to fix our broken housing market.
Britain will always be open to anyone who wants to live, work and build a life here.
It is, however, unfair that it is as easy for individuals who do not reside in the UK, as it is for foreign companies, to buy a home as it is for hard-working British residents.
For far too many people, the dream of access to property has become remote and the misery of the homeless remains too real.”
Jack Ross: My ultimate ambition is to lead Scotland.
Sunderland technician Jack Ross says his “ultimate ambition” is to become the Scottish coach at some point.
The 42-year-old Scot takes pleasure in taking up the challenge of reviving the North East club, which currently occupies third place in Ligue 1, three points behind the leader.
He joined the Stadium of Light this summer after taking St Mirren to the Scottish Premier League last season.
“I wanted to play for my country as a player.
I was selected for Division B and that’s it,” Ross told BBC Scotland’s Sportsound.
“But I grew up watching Scotland’s Hampden games with my dad and that’s something I’ve never forgotten.
This opportunity would only present itself if I succeeded in the management of the club.”
Ross's predecessors as Sunderland's selectors were Dick Advocaat, David Moyes, Sam Allardyce, Martin O'Neill, Roy Keane, Gus Poyet and Paulo Di Canio.
The former Alloa Athletic technician says he has not hesitated to line up behind such iconic names in such a big club, having already declined the proposals of Barnsley and Ipswich Town.
“For me, the success of the moment will be measured in the light of the question ‘can I bring this club back to the Premier League?’
Due to the structure and infrastructure of this club, it undoubtedly belongs to the Premier League,” he added.
“It’s not easy to get there, but I probably wouldn’t consider myself a success here unless I manage to bring the club back there.”
Ross has only three years as a coach, after a stint as an assistant at Dumbarton and 15 months as a coach at Hearts.
He then helped Alloa recover from a third-division relegation and turned St Mirren, who was on the verge of relegation, into a great championship winner the following season.
Ross says he feels more comfortable now than during his career at Clyde, Hartlepool, Falkirk, St Mirren and Hamilton Academical.
Alloa’s care “was probably a real crossroads,” he recalls.
“I really thought being a coach was better for me than playing.
It seems strange because I did well, made a good living, and enjoyed some nice highs.
But playing is sometimes difficult.
There are a lot of details to be worked out every week.
I continue to experience this in terms of stress and tension at work, but being a coach is fine with me.
I’ve always wanted to lead and now I do, I feel more comfortable in my skin than I’ve been in my entire adult life.”
Find the entire interview on Sportsound on Sunday, September 30 on Radio Scotland between 12:00 and 13:00 BST.
According to a survey, the ideal time for a pint is 5:30 p.m. on Saturday.
The heat of summer has boosted the income of struggling British pubs, but has added to the pressure on restaurant chains.
Figures indicate that bar and pub groups recorded a 2.7% increase in sales in July, but restaurant revenues fell 4.8 percent.
Peter Martin, of the consulting firm CGA, which compiled the data, said: “England’s continued sunshine and longer-than-expected participation in the World Cup meant that July followed the June model, where bars had risen 2.8%, except for restaurants, which suffered an even bigger shock.
The 1.8% drop in the restaurant sector in June only worsened in July.
Pubs and bars where alcoholic beverages are served are by far the most popular, with more points of resemblance than restaurants that decline.
Food pubs have also suffered from the effects of the sun, but not as much as restaurateurs.
It seems that people just want to go out for a drink.
In pubs and bars, beverage sales increased by 6.6% over the month and food decreased by 3%.”
